{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"indigoid-unmystic-serpent","description":"## Why\n\nStatic wiring tests cannot prove that an LLM criterion distinguishes concrete breakage scenarios from harmless silence or valid project customization. A balanced, repeatable evaluation is needed before the blocking project criterion is considered ready.\n\n## What\n\nAdd a project criterion evaluation corpus, add structural tests for that corpus, run the existing live evaluation runner, and tune only the project rubric if calibration exposes false positives or missed portability failures.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn scope:\n\n- `.rebar/evals/plan-review-project-portability.eval.yaml`\n- `.rebar/prompts/plan-review-project-portability.md`, only for calibration-driven rubric adjustments\n- `tests/unit/test_project_portability_eval.py`\n- live evaluation of `project.portability`\n\nOut of scope:\n\n- core registry, verifier, or disposition changes\n- coaching move behavior\n- existing portability debt\n- adding requirements for client-agnostic wording\n\n## Approach\n\nUse the existing `rebar criteria eval` path against a balanced corpus. Must-fire cases cover: a Gerrit landing command added to core, Python-only review rules added to core, a macOS-only dependency, and an assumed local checkout or unrestricted filesystem in remote MCP operation. Must-not-fire cases cover: no portability discussion, rebar-specific behavior in project configuration, an explicitly surface-scoped additive CLI feature, and a portable implementation with supported alternatives.\n\nRun each case three times. The release threshold is recall `1.0`, false-accept rate `0.0`, per-case stability of at least two of three runs, and Cohen kappa of at least `0.70`. If the threshold is missed, revise only the project rubric and rerun until it passes; do not weaken Pass 2 or Pass 3.\n\n## Dependencies\n\nDepends on the criterion-integration child because calibration executes the activated project criterion and its authored rubric.\n\n## Test Strategy\n\nValidate corpus structure deterministically, then use the live criterion evaluation command for semantic calibration. Record the model, timestamp, run count, and aggregate metrics on this ticket so the external LLM result is auditable by the completion gate.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The eval corpus contains the four named must-fire cases and the four named must-not-fire cases with explicit expected outcomes. Prove with `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability_eval.py -k balanced_corpus`.\n- [ ] Every must-fire case requires a plan citation, alternate supported client shape, causal mechanism, and observable breakage scenario in the returned finding. Prove with `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability_eval.py -k finding_contract`.\n- [ ] Every must-not-fire case represents either silence, valid project configuration, explicit surface scoping, or a portable alternative. Prove with `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability_eval.py -k negative_boundaries`.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] Three live runs meet recall `1.0`, false-accept rate `0.0`, per-case stability of at least two of three, and Cohen kappa of at least `0.70`; a ticket comment records the command, model, timestamp, run count, and metrics. Prove with `.venv/bin/rebar criteria eval project.portability --runs 3 --output json`.\n- [ ] Any calibration-driven prompt edit remains confined to the project rubric and preserves the four-part finding contract. Prove with `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability_criterion.py tests/unit/test_project_portability_eval.py`.\n","id":"21dd-8681-4447-4bc0","parent_id":"jira-reb-1003","priority":2,"tags":["plan-review","portability","evaluation"],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Calibrate the portability criterion"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784164046580160001,"uuid":"c67ac530-47e4-4eff-8503-b61f53755b61"}